From: stopless-java-gc <noreply@anthropic.com>
Subject: [PATCH 0060/N] globalDefinitions.hpp: HeapWord = 16 bytes under CHERI purecap (MOJO-aligned)

This replaces an earlier "HeapWord = 8-byte struct" attempt (see
patches/disabled-pre-mojo16/0060-heapword-metaword-typedef-cheri-8byte-struct.patch
and follow-on patches 0056, 0058, 0059, 0061, 0062, 0063).

Background. HotSpot defines HeapWord as `HeapWordImpl*` (opaque
pointer). On standard LP64, sizeof(HeapWord) = 8 and `LogHeapWordSize
= 3` makes `1 << LogHeapWordSize == sizeof(HeapWord)` hold.

On CHERI purecap, sizeof(pointer) = sizeof(capability) = 16. The
previous attempt forced HeapWord back to 8 bytes via a struct
typedef and then suppressed every downstream invariant
(`HeapWordSize == wordSize`, metaspace alignment, SIMD strides, ...)
— six follow-on patches, several marked TEMP.

MOJO (Manchester + THG, public CHERI-Tech 2023 slides + Feb 2024
blog) reports keeping HeapWord as a pointer and accepting that
HeapWord becomes 16 bytes on Morello CheriBSD, with heap math
throughout treating HeapWord as the 16-byte addressing unit.

This patch adopts that approach:

  1. HeapWord = HeapWordImpl* (unchanged from upstream — naturally
     16 bytes on purecap).
  2. LogHeapWordSize = 4 under `__CHERI_PURE_CAPABILITY__` so
     `1 << LogHeapWordSize == sizeof(HeapWord) == 16` holds.
  3. HeapWordsPerLong = 1 forced (would otherwise be 8/16 = 0).
     Physically: each 16-byte HeapWord holds one jlong with 8 bytes
     slack. The three call sites that use HeapWordsPerLong
     (align.hpp align_up, accessBackend.inline.hpp divide,
     arguments.cpp MinObjAlignment assert) all assume >= 1.

Knock-on effect: assertion `1 << LogHeapWordSize == sizeof(HeapWord)`
in universe.cpp holds naturally (patch 0056 unneeded). genCollectedHeap
guarantee `HeapWordSize == wordSize` holds (patch 0062 unneeded).
Metaspace 16-byte alignment is automatic (patch 0063 unneeded). SIMD
strides of `4*wordSize` are correct again (patches 0058, 0059
unneeded). BinList smallest_word_size returns to upstream (0061
unneeded).

Cost: heap math operates in 16-byte units, so heap is roughly 2x
larger for same Java object count. Acceptable because purecap mode
already pays a 2x memory cost on every pointer-typed field.

Refs: docs/05_zgc_cheri_collision_report.md (patch 0060B)
      mojo-jvm.org "exactly-constrained-bounds" (Feb 2024)
      Glasgow CHERI-Tech 2023 slides "OpenJDK on Morello"

--- a/src/hotspot/share/utilities/globalDefinitions.hpp
+++ b/src/hotspot/share/utilities/globalDefinitions.hpp
@@ -229,12 +229,26 @@ typedef MetaWordImpl* MetaWord;
 // HeapWordSize must be 2^LogHeapWordSize.
 const int HeapWordSize        = sizeof(HeapWord);
 #ifdef _LP64
+#ifdef __CHERI_PURE_CAPABILITY__
+// CHERI purecap: HeapWord = HeapWordImpl* = 16-byte capability.
+const int LogHeapWordSize     = 4;
+#else
 const int LogHeapWordSize     = 3;
+#endif
 #else
 const int LogHeapWordSize     = 2;
 #endif
+#ifdef __CHERI_PURE_CAPABILITY__
+// CHERI purecap: HeapWord=16, jlong=8. BytesPerLong/HeapWordSize = 8/16 = 0
+// would divide-by-zero downstream. Force HeapWordsPerLong=1: each 16-byte
+// HeapWord holds one jlong with 8 bytes padding. align.hpp:align_up,
+// accessBackend divide, arguments MinObjAlignment assert all need >= 1.
+const int HeapWordsPerLong    = 1;
+const int LogHeapWordsPerLong = 0;
+#else
 const int HeapWordsPerLong    = BytesPerLong / HeapWordSize;
 const int LogHeapWordsPerLong = LogBytesPerLong - LogHeapWordSize;
+#endif

 // The minimum number of native machine words necessary to contain "byte_size"
 // bytes.
